    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-08-23T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-08-23T22:00:00-05:00" n="363"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d363">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163/189: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-08-24T11:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 24, 1927—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 24—4:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>830. Department’s 322, August 20, 2 p.m.<note n="38" xml:id="d363fn38">Not
                        printed.</note> Following from Lockhart: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“August 23, noon. No objection to return of women mission workers to
                            Hankow in limited numbers provided they reside in concession areas.
                            Residence outside of these areas and in Wuchang is not advisable as
                            protection in that event could not be afforded nor could evacuation in
                            case of an emergency be quickly and safely effected. Some of Bishop
                            Root’s workers would probably be employed at Wuchang where most of his
                            activities are centered. While conditions have improved at Wuchang they
                            are by no means settled and daily visits of women missionaries there at
                            present are not advisable.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>I concur in the foregoing.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
